node.text:
Are you planning to visit Rocky this summer? Then watch this video for details on the timed-entry system. Reservations are required for the park from 9 am to 3 pm, and 5 am to 6 pm for the Bear Lake Road Corridor.

Reservations for the month of August will
be released on July 1, at 10 am MST.

If you can't get a reservation, you can still enter the park before 9 am or after 3 pm. For Bear Lake Road Corridor before 5 am or after 6 pm. Be aware of traffic delays starting around 8 am, and again around 3 pm. Plan accordingly, especially in the morning!

NPS / A. Andreas

node.text:
On Wednesday, October 21, the East Troublesome Fire ran approximately 18 miles before it moved into the west side of Rocky Mountain National Park. It then spotted approximately 1.5 miles from the head of Tonahutu Creek on the west side of the Continental Divide to the head of Spruce Creek on the east side of the Continental Divide. Rapid evacuations took place in Grand Lake on October 21. Evacuations for the majority of the Estes Valley were implemented on October 22, as weather predictions forecast major winds on the night of October 23 through October 24 pushing the fire further to the east. Firefighting actions and favorable weather on October 24 and 25 helped halt the major movement of the East Troublesome and Cameron Peak Fires. 

The following video demonstrates first-hand the impacts of the East Troublesome Fire. It is a somber reflection and an important part of our understanding. 

Approximately 30,000 acres, or 9 percent of the park, has been impacted by the East Troublesome and Cameron Peak Fires. 

Our park staff are working to create a path forward for those areas that were most impacted. 

We have felt the support and concern of so many who have a deep sense of place and attachment to their beloved Rocky Mountain National Park.  Thank you! ❤

#COFires #EastTroublesomeFire #CameronPeakFire #forestfire

node.text:
2020 has been quite the year. Now more than ever, we are using our public lands as a place to escape from it all. We want to take a moment to thank the volunteers who help keep our parks a great place to visit. Through the COVID-19 pandemic, resulting staff shortages, and multiple wildfires, our amazing volunteers have stood by our side as we worked to keep the Park operating safely. You help us keep Rocky rockin’ and we are grateful to have such a dedicated group of people. Thank you volunteers!

#rmnp #volunteers

Song: In My Soul - Liam.M

NPS / Aubry Andreas

node.text:
Welcome home! This year, Rocky Mountain National Park will welcome new residents: over 7,000 boreal toads. The boreal toad is an endangered species in Colorado. 

The park is working with @rmconservancy, @usgs, @coloradostateuniversity, @coparkswildlife, and Colorado Natural Heritage Program on the reintroduction effort.

#ParkScience #ParkPartners

node.accessibility_caption: A black bear holds its paw up.

node.text:
Rocky’s black bears give our #JuniorRangers a big high five for helping to keep them safe. Black bears will eat just about anything and right now are especially hungry as they prepare for winter. During this time scientists call hyperphagia, bears eat between 15,000 and 20,0000 calories per day! Ensure trash and scented items are properly stored to encourage black bears to find their own food and stay out of trouble. 

Image Credit: NPS/Shonalau

node.accessibility_caption: Graphic of a person jumping betwwen rocks while a marmot watches. Says "Parkour! Rock hop to protect tundra plants."

node.text:
"Parkour!" - Michael Scott - Visitors exploring the alpine tundra

It can be easy to get lost in the wonder of the alpine tundra, but whether you're trying to get that perfect photo or simply explore, it's up to you to help us preserve this ecosystem for future enjoyment.

Your mission when exploring off trail:

✅Get from point a to point b without trampling tundra vegetation. You can do this by rock hopping or stepping in areas where there's no vegetation.

✅Stay on the trail if in a tundra closure area.

✅Leave rocks and flowers as you found them. Plants use rocks as shelter and absorb heat from them.

Rocky Mountain National Park does not endorse attempting jumps from significant heights, 360 degree spins, or backflips....

NPS / A. Andreas

#YearoftheTundra #KnowYourImpact

Pika, marmot, and bighorn sheep aren't the only things you can spot at Rock Cut this summer! You can also find our vegetation crew working on restoring an unestablished trail. 

Please remember to stay on the trail when in a Tundra Closure area as these are areas that have been heavily impacted and need to be revegetated.

NPS / A. Andreas

#YearoftheTundra #KnowYourImpact #TundraTuesday

node.text:
Our first student feature is Seth Israel whose work focuses on the animals of the tundra! 

"Coming from the prairies that encompass the wonderful University of Kansas, I wanted to capture the incredible wildlife supported by the alpine-tundra - an incredibly fragile ecosystem supported along a very thin stretch along North America. To capture the diverse populations that co-exist, I illustrated, carved, and printed five distinct creatures: The Bighorn Sheep, Elk, Marmot, Pika, and a Ptarmigan. Hope you enjoy my works - these are my first attempts at print-making!"

#YearoftheTundra

node.text:
The Rocky Mountain Columbine (Aquilegia caerulea) is blooming all across our park – from Glacial Gorge to the Kawaneechee Valley and even as high as Rainbow Curve. Known as the Colorado state flower, this bi-colored masterpiece traces its common name back to the Latin word for dove, columba. Can you imagine how the flower resembles a cluster of five birds with their heads together? Those spurs – or the heads of doves – hold sips of nectar for pollinators to help it reproduce. 

As the state flower, it is illegal to pick it anywhere in the state; while you’re visiting Rocky, please don’t pick flowers so humans and pollinators alike can continue to savor the colorful landscape for generations to come! 

Learn more about wildflowers at Rocky: https://www.nps.gov/romo/learn/nature/wildflowers.htm

Image Credit: NPS/Schonlau 
#RecreateResponsibly #FindYourPark #EncuentraTuParque #WildflowerWednesday

node.text:
With increased visitation comes increased impacts to the park. Due to the fragile nature of the alpine tundra, this area of the park is impacted the most. Did you know that many of the "trails" you may come across are actually social trails created over time by visitors walking in the same area?

The last two photos show some of the social trails that have been made over the last few years. You can help reduce this impact on the tundra by staying on established paved trails, spreading out if you travel off trail, and respecting tundra closures in the park!

NPS Images / C. Ling; R. Eckert

#YearoftheTundra #TundraTuesday #KnowYourImpact

Image of a different visitor created social trail. Says "It only takes 8 to 15 times of walking in an area to make a social trail. Here in the alpine, it could take even less. To reduce this impact, stay on official trails, spread out if traveling off trail, and respect tundra closure areas."

node.text:
To help commemorate the Year of the Tundra, the park welcomed a group of students from the University of Kansas School of Architecture and Design. They spent a week exploring the alpine tundra, becoming (not so) Junior Rangers, and creating art inspired by the landscape. For many, this was the first time experiencing this ecosystem and it's now one of their favorite places in the park! Did you catch their pop-up exhibit at Hidden Valley last week?

Stay tuned as we share their work in the coming weeks!

Photo 1: Group photo of the students with their professor.

Photo 2: Carefully standing between vegetation, a park ranger provides a program to students about the alpine tundra ecosystem.

Photo 3: An early stage of a student's work. This student utilized cutouts to merge both nature and art together. 

Photo 4:  Students show their art to park rangers while explaining the inspiration for their work.

Photo 5: Students are sworn in as official Rocky Mountain National Park Junior Rangers.

NPS images 

#YearoftheTundra

node.text:
The alpine tundra ecosystem is one of the most distinct aspects of Rocky Mountain National Park. In this “land above the trees” where winter winds can exceed 120 mph and summer temperatures peak in July at an average of only 52°F, many plants are dwarfed – but still packing a big punch. 

For instance, the dwarf willow (Salix artica), one of the smallest woody plants in the world, grows only a few months per year to ½ - 2 ½ inches tall and just one ounce of its buds contain 112,000 calories. Foraging on these nutrient-rich buds, the ground-dwelling ptarmigans can gain weight for winter! 

Learn more about the alpine tundra ecosystem: https://www.nps.gov/romo/learn/nature/alpine_tundra_ecosystem.htm

Image Credit: NPS/Ritchey
#ThatsAmazing #FindYourPark #EncuentraTuParque

node.text:
¡Mira! Es un pájaro… es un avión… es un guardaparques!     

Los guardaparques son cuidadores de tierras publicas y son tan diversos como las experiencias dentro de estos lugares especiales. Esta semana los guardaparques en el Parque Nacional de las Montañas Rocosas están emocionados de recalcar los antecedentes y experiencias únicos que cada visitante, guardaparques juveniles y guardaparques trae a los Prques Nacionales. Únase a nosotros en la celebración de  Latino Conservation Week durante el 17 al 25 de julio. Esta semana ofrece una oportunidad para la comunidad de Latinx se una y demuestre su pasión por la naturaleza- tanto su disfrute y su preservación. Obtenga mas información sobre esta tradición y como puede celebrar aquí: https://go.nps.gov/LatinoConservationWeek2021 

¿Cómo vas a celebrar Latino Conservation Week? 

Look! It’s a bird… it’s a plane… it’s a park ranger! 

Park rangers are caretakers of public lands and are as diverse as the experiences within these special places. This week park rangers at Rocky Mountain National Park are excited to highlight the unique backgrounds and experiences that every visitor, junior ranger, and park ranger brings to National Parks. Join us in celebrating Latino Conservation Week from July 17-25. This week provides an opportunity for the Latinx community to come together and to demonstrate their passion for the outdoors-both its enjoyment and preservation. Learn more about this tradition and how you can celebrate here: https://go.nps.gov/LatinoConservationWeek2021 

How will you celebrate Latino Conservation Week? 
 
Hashtag(s); #JuniorRanger #GuardabosquesJuveniles #LatinoConservationWeek #LCW2021 #EncuentraTuParque  #FindYourPark #ExplorarAprenderProteger #LearnExploreProtect   #RecreateResponsibly #RecrearResponsablemente 
Image Credits; NPS Photo/D. Roberts

node.text:
You love Rocky and want to enjoy and protect your national park - so do we! We hope you can take the time to become informed about the totality of Rocky’s 44 percent increase in visitation (2012 to 2019). If you weren’t able to attend - watch one of our webinars from May about long-range planning - learn more about key issues, desired conditions for day use visitor access, potential management strategies, Q & A of National Park Service staff and information on how to provide formal written comments on this first phase through July 19. This is just a step in the long-range planning process but not the end, there will be more opportunities for public involvement looking at more developed strategies ahead. The NPS mission directs us to preserve and protect park resources, and provide opportunities for outstanding visitor experiences for this and future generations. We are eager for the public to get engaged and be part of the solution as we develop management strategies to address Rocky’s long-term day use. 

Learn more: https://www.nps.gov/romo/getinvolved/day-use-visitor-access-strategy.htm

NPS/Photo

node.text:
Look, Simba, everything the light touches…is where one should tread lightly - Mufasa, probably.

It can take hundreds of years for the alpine tundra to recover from seemingly minor impacts like walking off trail. When vegetation is trampled, non-native plants get the opportunity to outcompete many native plants that wildlife depend on. Here are some tips to do your part when exploring the tundra:

✅ Check that you're not in a closure area
Tundra closures protect fragile alpine tundra from damage caused by heavy, concentrated foot travel. Off-trail hiking is prohibited within 100 yards of the trails and parking lots in these areas. Closures are found at:
 
  Forest Canyon Overlook
  Rock Cut
  Lava Cliffs
  Gore Range Overlook
  Alpine Visitor Center

✅ Stay on trail or rock hop
Staying on the trail is the best way to protect this fragile world. If you have to go off trail, rock hop or step in areas with no vegetation.

✅ Leave it how you found it
It takes many years for flowers to grow. Don't make it harder for them by picking them. Instead, take a photo!

#TundraTuesday #YearoftheTundra #KnowYourImpact

NPS / A. Andreas
